article.headline: Spurs score final six points
article.linkText: Visiting Spurs manage to hold off Suns
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Tony Parker, who had a grand total of two assists entering the final minute, made two of the biggest plays in the Spurs' 86-84 victory over the Phoenix Suns on Friday night. Parker drove to the basket and passed to Rasho Nesterovic for a stuff that tied it at 84-84 with 36.5 seconds to play, then sank the game-winner from 22 feet with 3.8 seconds left. It was his fifth basket in 13 attempts. "They tried to double-team so I kept the ball and let the clock go down," Parker said. "And I was confident to take that shot and make it." The way the Spurs were shooting, coach Gregg Popovich insisted he didn't care who took the shot. "I had no clue who was going to take it. I had no idea," Popovich said. "I just wanted anybody who might make a shot to take it." The Suns have made major personnel changes since giving the Spurs serious trouble in last year's playoffs. "But it's the same game plan," Duncan said. "They attack us the same way. They guard the same way." The Spurs trailed 84-80 after Shawn Marion's driving floater capped a 6-0 Suns' spurt with 1:25 to play. But Phoenix committed three of its 20 turnovers the rest of the way. Duncan, who had 25 points and 12 rebounds, sank a nine-footer and was fouled but missed the free throw and the Spurs trailed 84-82 with 1:08 left. Jake Voskuhl threw the ball away for Phoenix, and Parker drove the lane, then passed to Nesterovic to tie it at 84-84 with 36.5 to play. Joe Johnson, who scored eight of his 16 points in the fourth quarter, lost control on a drive, then Parker sank his long jumper. After a timeout, Voskuhl's pass to Johnson was knocked away for a jump ball with one-tenth of a second to play. The Spurs controlled the tip as the game ended. Marion had 23 points and 11 rebounds for the Suns. Casey Jacobsen was 6-for-6 shooting, five of them 3-pointers to match his career high of 17 points. Voskuhl grabbed a career-high 16 rebounds. Suns coach Mike D'Antoni would have preferred Jacobsen take the last shot, and blamed himself for late instructions that led to the turnover. "I really wanted to Casey to come off to the side and hit a 3 to win the game, because I didn't want to go to overtime," D'Antoni said. "But my last words coming out of the huddle was, if Joe's open, we take the layup." The Spurs had shot 4-of-19 in the fourth quarter before their final surge. San Antonio took 34 more shots than Phoenix did -- 92 to 68. Nesterovic scored 16, Hedo Turkoglu 12, Parker 11 and Manu Ginobili 10 for San Antonio. Johnson shot 5-of-16 to snap his five-game streak of scoring at least 20 points. With Duncan resting on the bench, Phoenix scored the first eight points of the fourth quarter to take its first lead since the opening minutes, 70-69, on Johnson's driving layup with 8:31 to play. Turkoglu sank a 3-pointer, and Nesterovic followed with a three-point play to put San Antonio back on top, 75-70. Jacobsen's fifth 3-pointer cut it to 75-73 with 6:36 left, and Johnson's baseline drive put Phoenix up 78-77 with 4:04 to play. Marion's floater tied it at 80-80 with 3:14 left. Duncan scored 12 in the third quarter, including consecutive bank shots of 15 and 16 feet, and San Antonio led by as many as nine. Jacobsen's fourth 3-pointer cut the lead to 59-55 with 6:37 left in the third, but Duncan made a rebound basket and the Suns went the next 3:56 without a field goal. The Spurs led 69-62 entering the fourth quarter. There were 22 turnovers -- 12 by the Suns and 10 by the Spurs -- in a sloppy first half that had San Antonio leading 51-44 at the break.

Game notes
Suns starting guards Johnson and Leandro Barbosa were a combined 2-for-14 in the first half. ... The Spurs had just two turnovers in the second half. ... The Suns were without Amare Stoudemire for the third consecutive game after he reinjured his left ankle and a right toe. He will make the team's five-game road trip that begins Sunday at Minnesota. ... Tommy Nunez, who retired last season after 30 years as an NBA referee, was presented with an achievement award by Suns owner Jerry Colangelo during a first-quarter timeout.
